A nurse in observation was made aware of a patient feeling faint around 1430. This nurse responded to this patient. She stated patient looked gray and said his oxygen saturation was 78%. His blood pressure was 88/60. She poured cold water on his chest, thinking he could be overheated. She instructed another nurse to call 911.  A call went out over the walkie-talkie for a Charge Nurse to come to the scene at 1440. At this time the other nurse was already on the phone with EMS. When I arrived to patient around 1441, patient's oxygen saturation was 99% and pulse was 80. He was pale. He was talking coherently. He stated he had not eaten all day. I gave him some hard candy to suck on.  Around 1445, EMS arrived. They assessed him and determined he did not need additional care.  He signed EMS forms and the patient's brother drove him home. Patient was advised to make sure he did not go a whole day without eating before getting his second dose of the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient sat in observation area after receiving vaccine for 15mins. After his time was up, he was asked if he was feeling okay, if so he may leave. He stood up and walked to pharmacy counter to inform pharmacy staff he was not feeling well, that he was having chills and felt dizzy. A pharmacist was called to check on the patient, as the pharmacist reached to patient to ask about his symptoms, the patient started to fall. The pharmacist caught the patient from behind and gently sat him down. A second pharmacist was called while another technician dialed EMS. EMS arrived to evaluate patient and determined he was dehydrated. They offered to take patient to ambulance to give him IV fluids, the patient declined. Stated he was fine, gave his statement and was able to walk out on his own power.
LAB_DATA: Per EMS: low potassium, low sodium. Likely hyponatremic and dehydrated

Took 2 Zzquil ~1am to help with sleep; slept through the night and woke ~8:20am. Napped again ~9am-12pm. Took 600mg ibuprofen upon rising. Remaining symptoms: full-body aches (especially right arm and torso), headache, swollen lymph nodes, mild fatigue.

Friday April 2, 2021 ? Got Phizer COVID shot at noon.  No reactions that day  Saturday 4/3 ? Woke up to body aches, fatigue, and sweats.  Fever of 100.4 most of the day. ? Stayed in bed and slept until 6:00.  Did not eat or drink much today. ? Felt dizzy when I got up.  Drank water and had 2 bananas and � a bowl of chicken soup. ? Felt the same all day.    Easter Sunday 4/4  ? Felt better but still fatigued.  Body aches were not as bad, and temp was normal. ? Drank a lot more water and had a little to eat in the morning. ? Kids came over for Easter Brunch.  We ate about 11:00. ? Whenever I stood up quickly, I got very dizzy.  Happened quite a few times throughout the day (I never had this problem before). ? When walking into the kitchen from outside, I got very dizzy and could not get up the steps on my own, I just kind of stopped.  Did not black out but felt close.  The kids helped me in, and I sat down.   ? Drank more water and took it easy. ? The kids left about 2:00.  Before they left, friend told me to go to a fire station and have my blood pressure checked. ? 2nd friend took me to 3 fire stations before we found one open, south of hardware store? They were nice, took my blood pressure, oxygen level and an EKG. ? They thought I was experiencing A-FIB.  Told me to go to the emergency room right away.  Wanted me to go by ambulance but I told them 2 friend could take me.  They recommended medical center , which was better equipped for this.   ? Got to the emergency room about 4:30 and checked in. ? Nurse checked me out and asked a lot of questions.  I gave her the EKG print out from the fire station.   ? She had us go back to the waiting area and was going to talk with the doctor.  ? After a while they took us back to emergency ward and plugged in a saline bag and monitor.   ? They hooked me up to an EKG machine again and took a reading. ? The doctor. came in and diagnosed me with A-FIB and discussed what it is, what can happen and how to treat it. She said that this could be a temporary episode of A-FIB or it could be permanent. ? She put me on a blood thinner and had me make an appointment with my cardiologist, Dr.    Monday 4/5: ? Felt better got dizzy a couple of times but drank a lot of water and ate. ? Finally got the blood thinner prescription at about 4:00.  Tuesday - Friday: ? Kept drinking a lot of water.  No real issues with dizziness.

He is treated with IV fluids for his dizziness and decreased oral intake over the last day secondary to his vaccine.  EKG returns and demonstrates new onset atrial fibrillation which is already rate controlled likely as patient is on metoprolol for his cardiomyopathy.  EKG is nonischemic.  Patient's labs returned and are unremarkable.  Electrolytes are within normal limits.  Troponin is within normal limits and EKG is nonischemic making acute coronary syndrome unlikely.  Patient has a HEART score of 3 making him low risk for acute coronary syndrome.  I discussed the case with cardiologist Dr. who agrees that since patient is doing well he can be discharged home to follow-up in clinic.  She does recommend initiating apixaban therapy for his atrial fibrillation as his CHA2DS2-VASc score is 2.  I discussed this with patient and discussed risks and benefits of apixaban.  I discussed his stroke risk with him.  After discussion patient is amenable to initiating apixaban therapy.  I did discuss avoiding sports in which he could have traumatic brain injury as he is high risk for bleeding when initiating anticoagulation.  Patient understands and is amenable to this plan.  He is started on apixaban and will follow up in clinic with his cardiologist Dr. He has been given strict return precautions and discharged in stable condition.    The patient will return for new or worsening symptoms and is stable at the time of discharge. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Around 5:30 pm on Friday night, I started feeling really cold; couldn't get warm for 2 hours. Then I started getting a fast heart rate; checked this around 7 pm; BP was 181/80 and heart rate was 135.  I was starting to feel warm along with being cold.  I had a gradually increasing temperature; checked it around 8:30 pm; was 102.1; took 2 tylenol and temperature slowly started going down.  My heart would not slow down; I sat in my recliner and kept deep breathing and had calming herbal tea; was afraid to go to the ER due to Covid.  After more than 4 hours with a racing heart, I felt exhausted and laid down around 12:30 a.m. and fell asleep.  I woke around 3 am with nausea and soaking wet pajamas from sweating.  I fell asleep again and woke around 7 am; I felt very tired, woozy and my heart hurt.  I felt a bit more normal after a few days.  I still feel a bit dizzy and light headed.  I was concerned when I later heard some J&J vaccines were contaminated; on 4/2/21, I called the pharmacy because the number they wrote on my card, 1805D18 wasn't clear; they told me this # was incorrect and should be 037A21B and couldn't explain why this was so. They were going to check into  this and call me; I called them again on 4/5/21 and was told the correct # was 043A21A and that the vaccine was from the Netherlands.  They couldn't offer any more information or explain why the initial # was incorrect. I find this concerning and have been unable to find an answer.
OTHER_MEDS: multi vitamin, calcium with vit D, tumeric

Patient seen at the Vaccination Center on 4/9/2021.   He had just received his first dose of COVID-19 vaccine.     He was feeling dizzy and felt like he was going to pass out.   He was transported by EMT to the Adverse Reaction Area and then moved.    Representative served as sign language interpreter via tablet.   His wife was also present and is deaf.     Patient stated that his heart rate was very slow, and he felt dizzy, hot, and sweating.  He also fel very weak and it appeared that was going to pass out.  He was also shaking.   Ambulance was called due to the above symptoms.  Patient also stated that he thought he may need to go to the ER.     Vital signs:  9:53 am: Blood pressure was 143/71, heart rate was 71.   Patient was given an ice pack.  He also took sips of water.   He then noted that he felt better, after laying down.    Ambulance crew arrived and he declined to go the ER.    He got up and walked around stated the he felt better.     He notes that his head feels like it's slightly buzzing, so he lay down again.   Vitals signs:   10:25 am: Blood pressure 138/63, heart rate is 64, temperature is 98.1   Patient felt better and noted no more buzzing in his head.  He also walked around and felt normal.    Patient notes that he blacked out as a child whenever he got shots/injections.  He was not surprised that this happened to him today.   He wanted to know whether he should get the second vaccine injection.  It is recommended that he get his second vaccine injection and we also discussed that he may have the same reaction as today.  He should allow for extra time and be well-hydrated.     He felt safe to go home and his wife would be driving him home.    Should he feel worse, then he should go to the ER.    The patient and his wife understand this.  All questions were answered.
HISTORY: Migraine w/o aura Atypical chest pain

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About I experienced headaches and no fever in 24 hours following my first dose of the Moderna COVID19 vaccine, but about 48 hours later I experienced pain and itchiness with no rash on the soles of both feet and the palms of both hands. This pain and itchiness did lessen in intensity over time, but it has never gone away. I am also experiencing itchiness without a rash all over the skin of my body, including my vagina. When I scratch, red marks rise up on the skin and remain far longer than what is typical for my body. Areas of my body that itch include scalp, inside eyelids, lips, inside ears, outside ears, neck, between breasts, back, stomach, buttocks, thighs, legs, and especially my ankles and the tops of my feet.  The itchiness travels and I have learned to resist the urge to scratch. I went to see my physician for the first time yesterday since the sensation has not abated. I did take my second vaccine on schedule on March 26th (Moderna COVID-19 vaccine, Lot Number 038A21A.). I experienced headaches and a fever of 101F starting about 12 hours after the shot that lasted for 24 hours. The itchiness did not intensify, but it has also not abated.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 2/9 vaccine #1 around 0930.  Around 5pm notice neck was itchy, red and ?hot? feeling.   Over the next few weeks the neck got a more widespread redness, the creases of my elbows became red and itchy then behind my knees became red and itchy.   2/23 I noticed the rash has spread to my truck and was starting to itch on my shins. Called dermatology clinic.   2/24 Derm appt #1- saw the NP. She thought it looked like a viral rash. Started oral steroids 60mg x3 days then tapered down over 10 day period. Ordered Triamcinolone cream for topical treatment and Zyrtec twice a day, 25mg hydroxyzine at night for sleep  3/2- vaccine #2 due... was told to hold off until the rash cleared just to make sure   3/7- itching and redness returned to neck and spread to truck.   3/9- Derm appt #2. Noted the rash had changed in appearance and biopsied arm. Received a steroid shot, Ordered pepcid twice a day, Allegra twice a day.   3/17- severe redness (the most extreme pic), burning and itching. It felt like a terrible sunburn with itchy hives under it. I can?t even begin to describe that pain. Called the Derm clinic. They ordered clobetasol ointment and go see Dr the next day.   3/18- biopsy with no eosinophils and only extreme inflammation. Received a loading dose (2 shots) of dupixent.   3/25- reddness and itching return to neck and shoulders/trunk.   3/26- Called Derm. Ordered a 40mg steroid taper that will last 20 days total.   4/1- Dupixent shot (2mL)   4/6- Appointment with Dr. Ordered Singulair and keep other taking medications. Lab work ordered.
LAB_DATA: 3/9/21- Punch skin biopsy to right arm- final impression morbilliform eruption  4/9/21- lab work drawn. Results pending
HISTORY: I have an ASA in my heart. Follow it once a year with a  cardiologist

Approximately 5 minutes after the patient received his vaccination, he rested his head on the wall behind him in the chair he was being observed in and passed out and turned white. His wife began slapping his face and screaming his name and the observer called for me. I arrived within seconds and assisted his wife in moving him from the floor to the chair. Within seconds of getting his head to the ground safely, he came back to and was very sweaty, red in the face. He stayed on the ground laying down, and then sitting for approximately 25 minutes. During that time, he told us that he had previously passed out during 3 procedures done at doctors offices.  We got him an ice pack and a orange pop as he was complaining of being hot and having only eaten a granola bar all day. He was able to get up to a chair and sat there for an additional 5 minutes, before he was able to walk out on his own accord. I have spoken with the patient twice since, once last evening and once today and he reports he feels great now besides the expected body aches from the vaccination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Around 10pm on 4/7 I felt a sudden onset of body aches.  I had similar symptoms after the first vaccine so I knew this was an expected side effect and decided to take two Tylenol 500mg and go to bed.  I had a restless night with pain on the injection site, chills, and severe body aches.  At 8:30am on 4/8, I got out of bed and still feeling sick, thought of taking Tylenol again.  I didn't want to take medication on an empty stomach so I took two sips of milk and coffee and two bites of a cookie, when I started feeling severe nausea.  It was a very strong nauseous sensation.  I started sweating.  I stood up from the table to take the cup to the sink and my vision turned partially black.  I thought I had stood up too quickly, so I sat down again.  I walked back to the table and sat down. I felt I was loosing control of my body.  I stood up again with the intention of going back to bed, and started walking towards my bedroom.  I told my husband that I was seeing all black.  I don't recall what happened next.  My husband says that he was asking me if I was alright but didn't answer.  He walked towards me  and I fainted against the pantry door and he was able to hold me.  I lost consciousness for a few seconds.  Paramedics came and took me to emergency room. I was released 2 hours later.  Had a fever of 100.4C in the afternoon with chills and body aches.
LAB_DATA: On 4//2021: chest x-ray brain scan EKG blood work All normal

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 04/08/2021 at 1440 immediately after injection patient experienced dizziness, was clammy to touch, pale in color. Patient verbalized not feeling well. Blood pressure 160/82, pulse 70 bpm.  Pt became sweaty and laid down, continued with "wave of dizziness," so decided to alternate between standing and sitting. At 1500, symptoms continued. blood pressure 180/100 pulse 70 bpm, drinking water c/o some shakiness. 1510 blood pressure 164/84 still c/o waves of dizziness, clammy. No respiratory distress. 1520 blood pressure 180/100 pulse 85 bpm 97% O2. No longer feels clammy, states that he "feels normal other than lightheaded and dizzy. Seems to subside then comes back again." Examined skin: pt had slight erythema on upper chest, blanches when pressed. No itching sensation.  1530 blood pressure 182/102, pulse 85 bpm, 97% O2. "I feel dizzy when you take my blood pressure." When asked about his breathing pt states "breathing feels fine." 1540 no itching. Erythema appears more red and more spread out on chest. "just don't feel right" Still c/o waves of dizziness and states he feels like felt when he took bactrim approximately 12 years ago- slow onset- pt experienced rash and just overall "not feeling right." 1545 blood pressure 172/102 pulse 92 bpm 97% O2. Erythema appears better, not as spread out across chest, more condensed. "Dizziness still comes in waves." 1607 blood pressure 204/102, pulse 90bpm, 97% O2- clammy to touch. After discussing with patient and patients spouse, agree that patient needs to be seen by either PCP, Dr. or go to ER. At the time pt did not wish to go to ER. Wife proceeded to call Dr.'s office to see about getting him in. Pt then started to feel worse and like he needed to go to ER. offered to call for an ambulance, pt refused as his wife could take him and would probably be quicker. staff offered diphenhydramine and pt declined, stating he would wait until he got to ER for treatment. Pt appeared very anxious and nervous. transported him via wheelchair to his vehicle at 1620, his wife then drove him to ER. 04/09/2021 at 0828  I left a voicemail with pt for follow up.  0830 I called to get follow up on pt. I spoke with the nurse that treated the patient. Pt did indeed come to ER and was treated for a reaction. He was given a dose of benadryl and solumedrol. Pt verbalized feeling like he was having a severe anxiety attack and that his adrenaline was really high. Nurse stated that she agreed with him. Pt was later discharged that evening. No epinephrine use reported.

Pt. received the vaccine at approximately 2:44pm.  Before I could hand him his card, his hands began trembling and he looked pale.  I asked how he was feeling.  He reported feeling shaky, dizzy, and very hot.  I asked him if he was having any difficulty breathing, had tightness in his throat/airways, or even felt a tingle.  He said no.  Noting the time, I asked if he had eaten lunch.  I asked if he has ever felt this way before.  He said he had when he gets a "hypoglycemic attack."  While not diabetic nor on any medications, he said he will occasionally get very low blood sugar.  He said he had not eaten since early that morning.  Another employee brought some juice I requested.  I again asked him about symptoms related to anaphylaxis, to which was not an indication of an anaphylactic reaction.  I gave him the juice to sip.  I asked him again about symptoms.  Because he was still dizzy, I took his blood pressure/heart rate.  His BP was 160/119 and heart rate 96bpm.  His color became more gray over the next several minutes.  He was still too dizzy to stand, felt hot, shaky, and now nauseous.  He handed over the juice and was given a receptacle if he vomited.  We suspected a vasovagal response, but was still symptomatic after 10 minutes. Meanwhile, the other pharmacist tried to call his doctor's office.  We learned his doctor had moved away and he had not yet come in nor selected a new provider.   We asked him if he felt he needed to be seen by a doctor.  He said he did and agreed to us calling an ambulance.   The ambulance arrived around 3:10.  The EMTs took his BP.  It had come down, but he could not stand up without his knees buckling.  The EMTs got him on the stretcher and took him to the hospital.
LAB_DATA: Pt. reported to me that the ER gave him fluids and monitored him.  He said they believed it was a severe vasovagal response.  He has not yet followed up with a new doctor.

U/A found EMS with 56 yo F seated in stationary vehicle, CAO x 4, c/o N/V and dizziness approx 10 mins after receiving her Covid vaccine (Johnson & Johnson). Paramedic advised that pt had initial BP of 90 mmHG systolic, 12 lead showed sinus rhythm w/o ectopy, and that he attempted ODT zofran w/o success due to pt's vomiting, all prior to EMS arrival. Pt. denied CP, abd pain, diarrhea, fever, cough, HA, syncope, neck or back pain. Pt. stated she felt SOB immediately after vomiting. All assessments/interventions as noted in rest of ePCR. GCS= 15, skin pink, warm, diaphoretic. No obvious signs of trauma. Pt. assisted from vehicle to stretcher, secured w/ straps. VS taken, WNL. Abd. soft, non-tender to palpation. Cardiac monitor showed sinus rhythm, rate of 60 bpm. Pt. actively vomited x 3 while IV access attempted and established. Pt. given 4 mg zofran IV w/ improvement in N/V. Pt requested transport for further evaluation. During transport, pt's VS remained WNL, and pt stated she was feeling better, that dizziness and nausea had stopped. Noted occasional unifocal PVC on 4 lead as well as increase of HR to 124 bpm for approx. 3 seconds during transport, then returning to baseline of sinus rhythm or sinus brady. Pt. stated she normally had a low HR and BP, and had felt palpitations in the past, but no episodes of palpitations today, including during transport. Pt. transported COLD traffic to where pt care, 12 lead, and report were transferred to RN in triage w/o incident.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt was CAO x 4 upon EMS arrival. EMS 3 stated pt experienced a syncopal episode after getting her COVID vaccine. Pt had a brief LOC and was initially hypotensive. IV was initiated by EMS 3 and NS was started. VS were WNL upon EMS arrival. Pt skin was still pale and clammy during assessment. Pt stated this has happened in the past with shots and blood draws, however, she has never fully lost consciousness. Pt was still c/o dizziness. Pt requested transport to REX ER. Pt was on the cardiac monitor upon EMS 14 arrival and a sinus rhythm was noted. 12 lead revealed a sinus rhythm with no STEMI criteria met. Pt was able to stand and pivot onto the stretcher without incident. Pt secured via straps and loaded into the unit. Once in the unit, VS reassessed. NS was reduced to a KVO rate due to improvement in BP. Pt had received approx 200mL of NS at the time. Pt denied any chest pain, SOB, N/V, or abd pain. Pt only complaint was dizziness. Pt was initially very anxious and was coached through breathing techniques which improved her anxiety. EMS left en route to REX ER. Pt was monitored during transport with improvement in her condition. Pt skin color and condition improved and her VS remained WNL. Pt denied any complaints during transport other than dizziness which she reported was improving. EMS arrived at REX ER. Pt was taken into the ER triage area and was able to stand and pivot onto a wheel chair. NS DC'd, pt received approx 300mL total. Report given to the triage RN and care transferred to same.

Within a few hours of receiving the vaccine, I started feeling nauseated. Since the day I took the vaccine, my appetite has been nonexistent. A day later, I felt very tired and confused. I received the vaccine on Monday and I woke up in a panic on Wednesday morning. My heart was racing, palms were sweaty, I felt like I couldn't breathe and it seemed like I was having a panic attack when I woke up. From that point forward, I fell into a deep depression. At first I didn't connect it with the vaccine, but I kept feeling nauseated and then wondered if it was connected. The depression became unbearable and I felt suicidal by the next week. I finally contacted my doctor's office and had a telemed visit where I explained that I had the J&J vaccine the week before and these symptoms presented themselves afterward. The doctor put me on Zoloft and I HAVE been treated for depression in years past with that; however, I had not taken depression medication for about 8-10 years until this. Likewise, because my doctor put me on an anti-depressant, she also wanted me to see a counselor--which I have done. The medication is helping somewhat but I still don't have an appetite. I don't know if the vaccine had anything to do with the depression, but I wanted to report it just in case others have had similar symptoms.
LAB_DATA: No tests, just visits and prescription
OTHER_MEDS: OTC Calcium; Vit D; Multivitamin; Iron; Monthly B12 injection
HISTORY: Rectal Cancer but no recurrence (5 years out)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient at Vaccine Clinic on 4/9/2021.   Patient had received her second dose of COVID-19 vaccine (Pfizer).    She noted dizziness.   She was able to walk to the Adverse Reaction Area and noted headache and sensitivity to light.   Disposable pillow case was given to the patient to cover her eyes.  Vital signs: 11:42 am: Blood pressure 231/141, heart rate 99, while sitting  We asked the patient to lay down on the gurney.  11:55 am: Blood pressure 210/132, heart rate 94 11:56 am: Blood pressure 208/140, heart rate is 95  Patient felt slightly better and looked better, but the recommendation was for her to go to the ER as her blood pressure was significantly high.  We discussed the risks of stroke and/or heart attack.   Patient declined ambulance transport, and she and her husband agreed to go to the ER.  Her husband agreed to drive her to the ER.   I called ER triage desk and alerted them that the patient would be going to the ER.   The patient and her husband understand this.  All questions were answered.

Patient presented for his first vaccine dose. He later stated he felt a sensation of something moving through his arm after vaccine administered, then states he felt some increased anxiety, followed by cold sweats, and then lost consciousness.  He was noted to be unresponsive, initially with brief period of apnea, and was unresponsive to sternal rub by vaccine administration staff.  He was placed into a reclined position in the driver seat of his vehicle. He regained consciousness within a minute, and was normally responsive but with pale color noted to face and chest, diaphoresis, and thready pulse with bradycardia, HR 43.  Difficult to auscultate HR and breath sounds clear but shallow. EMS responded promptly and assisted with evaluation, with initial BP 80/50, SpO2 97%.  Patient became less responsive and started to lose consciousness again, but responded to questioning, then lost consciousness again. His feet were placed on the dashboard to elevate them, and he quickly regained consciousness, pulse improved to HR 86, and repeat BP after a few minutes was 140/76. Oxygen saturations briefly dipped to 90% then rebounded to 100%. He improved quickly, was normally responsive and able to drink orange juice. He had pale clammy skin on the face, neck and hands, and some facial flushing.  Patient was monitored for several minutes, had improvement in symptoms, and refused transport by stretcher to the ambulance. He was able to walk to the passenger side of his vehicle and was driven out of the vaccination facility and further monitored. Blood glucose noted to be 96, EKG normal with sinus rhythm, no acute ST or T wave changes or other acute abnormality.   Patient was offered transport to the hospital for further evaluation, but he declined. Symptoms resolved completely, he was monitored for resolution of symptoms. He reported prior similar symptoms after a hand laceration at work and after a dental visit. Risks discussed, prevention measures for second dose discussed. Encouraged follow up with PCP given recurrent vasovagal syncope. No signs of allergy noted.
LAB_DATA: EKG NSR HR 72bpm, no acute changes, Glucose 96.

Patient did say before vaccine that he has fainted in the past from previous vaccines. I had a Representative administer vaccine while i stood next to patient and talked with him as a distraction from the shot. After Representative gave the vaccine patient asked "did you give vaccine?", he then immediately started to sweat very hard and said he was light headed (he was sitting down), then his eyes rolled back and he slouched down in chair, at which point I held him so he did not fall on floor. He started to jerk and twitch, perhaps was having a seizure, and was sweating very hard. I held him in chair so he would not hit his head or get hurt. After about 30 seconds he regained consciousness and asked how long he was out. His T-shirt was soaked in sweat and he said he felt very dizzy. The Representative got him an ice pack and placed at base of neck, which he said helped alot.  I sat with him for 10-15 minutes until he said he felt fine. I asked if he needed medical care and he said he did not, just needed to sit for awhile, and said this has happened before. I gave him a chair to sit in after he was fully alert and he sat for close to half an hour, at which point he said he was back to himself and felt fine.  I did offer he could stay as long as needed and I could call anyone if he needed me too, he insisted he was fine and after about 45 minutes he left. I did call him the next day to check on him and he said he was fine.
PRIOR_VAX: he said he has fainted from flu shots in the past

Patient assisted to Trendelenburg position and remained lying for 20m. Patient developed chills and tremors during this time stating she was cold. Patient endorsed feeling back at baseline.  Provider released patient and patient discharged.  Of note, provider notes patient with vasovagal syncope and convulsions after receiving J&J COVID vaccine. Patient has history of vasovagal reactions.

March 29, approximately 4:30 PM, I began to experience chills and body aches, and noticed my teeth felt sensitive when I ate dinner. March 30, upon waking: Chills and aches were gone, but by 10 AM, my teeth continued to get more and more sensitive (it felt like I had been hit on the right side of my mouth) and my gum tissue became bulbous and sore around the sore teeth (6,7,8,25,26,27) and I wondered if I cracked a tooth somehow. However, the pain radiated to the right posterior teeth, and crossed to both incisors (top and bottom) on the left side. I would describe the pain as throbbing and acutely sensitive to room temperature air, pressure, hot and cold. this happened in a very short span of time, and I was awake and not clenching or grinding my teeth. March 30, afternoon: I called my dentist. He was out of town. I posted on social media, asking if anyone has had tooth pain post vaccine. There were a handful of anecdotal stories (first hand) with a similar issue, so I decided to wait and see if my issue would resolve similarly. April 6: Pain has been intermittently severe and dull over the past week. I see my dentist this afternoon to do an evaluation. He says the tissue looks odd - almost like a herpetic lesion trying to heal, both around tooth 26 and on the palate adjacent to 8. Also, it appears there is no longer any keratinized gum tissue around 26, and the tissue had receded dramatically on this tooth. The doctor takes photos and refers me to a periodontist for a tissue graft to save the tooth. April 9 (today): I have an appointment with a periodontist next week for an evaluation. My dentist assures me the area will need a graft. Today I have less pain, but the gingival inflammation around 26 has persisted. Since I don't know the outcome at this point, I can only hope that tooth 26 can be saved with a facial graft, but that is the course of action.
LAB_DATA: Periodontal probing, photographs and evaluation of the affected teeth.
HISTORY: Migraine headaches, former periodontal disease with no existing inflammation, pocketing or perio activity in the last three years. I see the dentist and hygienist every 6 months.

After receiving the second dose of the vaccine on Wednesday I started experiencing a myriad of symptoms starting that night during sleep. I had body aches, nausea and diarrhea starting earlier the next day then once I threw up once I started feeling better then broke a couple of fevers. By Friday, however, I was feeling much better. I went through the weekend feeling totally fine, then Monday came and I was really achy throughout my body in my joints. Then that night when I went to sleep the joint pain worsened drastically and I started feeling a pins and needles sensation throughout my extremities only.   I got no sleep that night from the pain. These body aches felt wildly different from those from the first immediate reaction.  From there, I got a COVID test, Flu, and strep test taken all of which came back negative. The pain continued to worsen unbearably so I went to the ER. There, they tried a few pain medicines to ease the pain. It was the most uncomfortable time I've ever spent in my body. The doctor said the vaccine essentially attacked my nervous system and I had no idea what was happening to me because it isn't being mentioned as a possible side effect. However, both doctors I visited said they have been seeing neurological adverse effects in the hospital following the vaccine rollout. The pain lasted for a full week, and as of this past Saturday I've been feeling much better. I am still dealing with the lasting effects, the pins and needles are very faint but still active every now and then and my calf muscles are extremely tight in the morning making it still hard to walk, and my knees ache often. I've been stretching to combat the issues in my legs and it's been helping. I'm hopeful the pins and needles sensation will completely go away very soon. It has been 9 days since the second adverse reaction started.
LAB_DATA: Blood tests were taken on 3/30/21 and everything came back perfectly normal and in range which allowed the doctors to give me more pain medicine.
OTHER_MEDS: Sprintec, ecchinecea, Zyrtec, fish oil and D3

Order for Benadryl 50mg IM obtained.  Along with instructions not to drive post administration of the Benadryl and to call EMS or report to the nearest ED if reported symptoms related to chest tightness did not improve.   2:08pm Benadryl 50mg IM given in right upper extremity.  Patients husband has arrived and is standing next to her.  Patient remains calm and in no apparent distress other than the symptoms previously reported.  2:18pm Patient states she feels woozy from the Benadryl, but no worse or better than previous.  Offered to call EMS, patient and husband declined. 2:30pm Nursing Supervisor onsite.  Patient re-evaluated by asking questions related to current symptoms. Patient instructed not to drive due to the potential for drowsiness related to the Benadryl administration.   2:45p Patient and husband left the vaccination area together.

Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine EUA Immediately after getting the vaccine, I experienced severe nausea for 10-20 minutes. I experienced no symptoms for 3-4 hours afterward, but then began to develop a low-grade fever,  muscle aches, a headache, and became nauseous again.  Around 12 hours after getting the vaccine, I developed a fever of 102 F, I began to experience severe muscle aches and cramps in my calves and abdomen. I also began to develop a much worse headache and lost partial vision in my right eye for a few hours. This is when I became violently nauseous, but I was unable to throw up, or defecate.  I was unable to sleep during this time, and at 2 am, my nausea peaked, and I threw up incredibly violently and incredibly suddenly. It was so violent, it caused me to pop a blood vessel in my eye, and gave me a sore throat. However, after throwing up, most of nausea subsided.  At this point, the vision began to return to my eye. 20-40 minutes after throwing up, I began to experience chills that lasted for up to an hour. Eventually, I slept at 4 am, but slept fitfully, and woke every 40 minutes to 2 hours.  At 7 am on the 9th, the nausea was completely gone the day after my vaccination, but the muscle aches and headaches were back. My fever was down to 101, and I took some Tylenol and slept fitfully until 2 pm when I woke up feeling significantly better.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the vaccine at approximately 1:08 pm.  Once administered I was instructed to sit in the auditorium for 15 minutes for observation.  During that time I had a few heartrate increases and nausea but nothing out of the ordinary or concerning.  After the 15 minutes, I walked out to my car and thankfully my husband had driven because what happened next would have caused an accident.  Our drive home is approximately 20 minutes from where vaccine was administered.  In the car I began to feel a tingling all over my body that gradually began to feel like ?pins and needles? (like when you sit on your legs for too long and they ?fall asleep?), with the worst of the feeling being in both of my hands. I began opening and closing my fingers to try and get them to feel normal.  By the time we pulled into the driveway, my hand had locked up in a weird position and I was no longer able to communicate with them and make them move.  They were temporarily paralyzed.  My husband opened the door for me because I wasn?t capable of doing so.  Once I stepped out of the car, my body began to convulse and shake.  We stood there for a few minutes because one, I couldn?t make my body cooperate and two, we didn?t want our children seeing me that way.  My husband kept asking me if he should call an ambulance.  Of course, he should have but I think he was so scared and shocked that he just didn?t know how to react.  I had trouble forming words and sentences at that point and could not tell him to call. I felt pretty calm considering what was happening to me and I could not control myself.  My husband decided to walk away from me and coerce me to go to him.  I stood there for a few minutes trying to communicate with my legs.  Once I took my first step, my body stopped shaking and I started to regain feeling in my hands.  I went and laid down for a bit and began to feel a bit better.  Around 7pm I was feeling extremely cold.  So cold that I put on three layers of clothing and two comforters to try and warm myself.  That did not work though, as it was more of a cold from nerve endings than it was from temperature.  I went to bed around 9pm but didn?t fall asleep until around midnight.  I was feeling waves of cold down my body. Like a skin prickling when you hear a beautiful song and you get goosebumps and your hairs stand up.  I woke around 3am to an extreme headache and a fever of 102.6.  I took Tylenol and went back to bed.  When I woke in the morning, I felt better but had weird and random muscle twitching.  For the past few days I?ve been suffering with extreme fatigue which is not like me at all.  Even when I?m tired, I can still manage to function throughout the day.  Not only have I been tired, my body is weak, my muscles are weak and my joints hurt. I?m hoping this ends soon and doesn?t get any worse. It will be two weeks this Sunday.

Woke up 3 times drenched last nights and had to sleep in different locations in the home becuase the bed was wet with sweat.

I believe my vaccination was administered incorrectly and administered subcutaneously instead of the required intramuscular  route as I have shooting tingling pains going down my arm since immediately after vaccination. The pain has slowly been getting worse and worse and after some research I am quite confident my vaccine was administered incorrectly based on the video I just watched on the CDC's websites showing how to administer Subcutaenous vaccines versus Intramuscular ones. The pharmacist exactly followed the video to administer my Pfizer Covid-19 Vaccine via the subcutaneous route and she squeezed my upper arm fat and injected me at a 45 degree angle. At the time, I remember thinking it was strange she did that as hsitorically I always had doctors vaccinate me and they NEVER squeezed my arm fat and always vaccinated me at 90 degress rather than 45 degrees. I am at a loss at what to do as I am confident the vaccine was NOT administered correctly and  my fingers tingle uncontrollably and I also have weird bruising all over my hand and arm. Aside from the pain, was the vaccination even effective? Or am I suffering now for no reasons.

Three weeks after my second dose my Rheumatoid Arthritis flared up all over my body and especially in my left arm. I had joint pain in all of my joints. I have a previous injury and arthritis in that shoulder. My shoulder was on fire and my hands swelled up. I saw my Rheumatologist and after I started on Prednisone the swelling in my joints had gone down and the pain was better. My symptoms improved  in three days.  I also have started back on Methotrexate once weekly and my Humira since then.

Felt ok by the time I was released from the 15 minute observation area. After driving about 5 minutes towards home, I started to get chest tightness and my throat felt strange and swallowing was not normal. I didn't feel well in general. No rash or hives. Breathing was ok. When I got home, I took 2 Benadryl. After two hours I felt much better except for the chest pain which felt like my "normal" atypical chest pain and lasted a little while longer. The chest tightness was gone though and the throat and swallowing had improved also.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was seen at offsite UNM-Gallup COVID vaccine event today 4/8/21. At ~1305, provider was asked  to assess this 35yo who had received her 2nd dose of Pfizer COVID vaccine at 1247, with complaint of itchy rash to neck and throat "tightening." She has a hx of multiple drug allergies and is on multiple medications as below for seizure disorder and other comorbidities. She had reported a hives rash after her first  dose of COVID vaccine 3wks ago. As such, she had taken 50mg benadryl at ~1200 today to attempt to prevent a reaction. On limited evaluation, her oral airway was clear without obvious angioedema. She did have hives to her neck and was quite pruritic. Her lungs were clear and she was moving air without wheeze. She began slurring her speech and seemed confused, which her family member reported is how she becomes before seizures.  With concern for anaphylaxis, gave a dose of 0.3mg IM epinephrine.  EMS was called to transfer patient to ED. Dose epi given at 1320, with almost immediate improvement in hives, pruritus and notable improvement in mentation and slurring of speech. EMS arrived at ~1325, patient found to have HR 106, BP 180/84 after epi. She was transferred in stable but acute condition.
LAB_DATA: Given Epi 0.3mg IM at vaccination site. Given Dexamethasone 10mg IV, diphenydramine 25mg IV, famotidine 20mg IV in emergency department. Chest x-ray, BMP, and CBC WNL.

I was nonresponsive when my fiance found me immediately following the crash, and was rushed to the hospital  via ambulance. Upon arrival to the hospital, my fever was found to be 102 F. 55-year-old male with no diagnosed past medical history presents emergency department after cardiac arrest.  Per patient's daughter, patient was feeling at baseline today.  He got his COVID vaccine at 5 PM this evening.  He was running some errands and called his daughter at 8:40 PM.  He told his daughter he was not feeling well.  She reports he sounded out of breath and sounded as if he was slurring his words.  Daughter told him to pull over and she called 911.  She met him on the side of the road and he was gasping for air.  She arrived at the same time as EMS.  Upon arrival of EMS patient was in ventricular fibrillation.  He was defibrillated 3 times.  He also had one episode of ventricular tachycardia.  He was given 300 mg of amiodarone and 3 rounds of epinephrine with had return of spontaneous circulation.  King airway was placed and patient was brought to the emergency department.

The patient received her J&J vaccine at 8:11 AM on 4/9/2021. Approximately 10 minutes later, her son reported that she was in the waiting area and experiencing increased heart rate and dizziness. The patient was asked if she would like us to contact EMS for her or to wait a few minutes to see if her condition would resolve. She decided to wait a few minutes for her condition to resolve. After approximately 5 more minutes, her son stated that he would like us to contact EMS, and they were contacted at that point. When EMS arrived, they were directed to the patient and allowed to monitor the patient for worsening condition. The patient's condition resolved, and EMS was no longer needed. The patient stated to the pharmacy that she was feeling  better and would seek medical attention later if she experienced more symptoms and then left the store.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received first dose of Pfizer at 12:50 pm on left deltoid, lot # ER8731, expiration date on 07/2021. Patient has a history of rheumatoid arthritis and asthma, both of which are controlled with medication. Patient waited in outdoor EMT waiting area for approximately 20 minutes. At 12:09 pm, patient entered indoor EMT waiting area and asked the lead nurse, if she could check her blood pressure. Upon assessment, patient was alert, oriented X4, clear speech. The patient's primary complaint was "feeling tired". The patient sat down in a chair in the observation area while RN took her blood pressure. At 12:09 pm, the patient's BP 156/102 sitting, HR 68, SpO2 97% RA, RR 17 res/min unlabored. Patient denies tightness in chest or throat, difficulty breathing, or trouble swallowing. Patient states she did not drink water today. RN gave patient a water. Patient consumed 16 oz of water at 1:13pm. Patient reports she is "feeling better" at 1:13 pm. At 1:16 pm, the patient's BP 156/102 sitting, HR 75, RR 18 res/min unlabored. Patient states her blood pressure "is usually low" because she runs daily, but she "can't remember" her usual range. At 1:20 pm, BP 150/100 sitting, HR 66, RR 18 res/min unlabored. Patient states she is "feeling tired and cold". Patient was transferred to anti-gravity chair at 1:25 pm with assistance from EMT. At 1:25 pm, patient's BP 167/115, RR 20 res/min, HR 64. At 1:32 pm, patient called her brother to come pick her up. Patient was provided with education related to signs and symptoms of allergic reaction, such as tightness in throat, tingling of tongue, and shortness of breath. Patient denies experiencing such symptoms. At 1:32 pm, BP 150/90, HR 70, Spo2 at 99%, RR 20 res/min. Patient states "I felt like something bad was going to happen" after receiving her vaccine. EMT talked with patient calmly and encouraged deep breathing. At 1:39 pm, BP 164/88, HR 84, Spo2 at 98%, RR 20 res/min. At 1:42, the patient requested to leave. Lead RN, advised patient to stay laying down and deep breath to help her blood pressure go down. Patient states "I want to leave". Patient was provided with education about normal blood pressure ranges. Patient verbalizes understanding and states she is aware she needs to call her doctor if she is experiencing headaches, vision changes, and/or chest pain. At 1:45 pm, patient got up out of chair and followed by EMT to car. Patient's gait was steady and balanced. Patient states she is "okay to drive". Patient declined having more vitals taken. Patient left with brother in passenger seat of car at 1:47 pm.

He denies chest pain, difficulty breathing, swelling of the face/lips/tongue/throat, skin rash/itching, cramping abdominal pain, and vomiting.     Exam (update as needed): GEN: Upon arrival, patient unconscious and not responsive to stimuli HEAD: NCAT EYES: pupils unreactive and mydriatic ENT: Ears normal, Nose normal, OP normal, no evidence of angioedema NECK: Supple, without LAD.  CV: RRR, no m/r/g, palpable strong radial pulse PULM: Clear to auscultation bilaterally, no accessory muscle use ABD: Soft, no tenderness. SKIN:  Skin pale, cool, and clammy.  No rashes.  No erythema or edema of the injection site. MSK: FROM, MS 5/5 NEURO: Patient unconscious upon arrival.  CN 2-12 grossly intact, no ataxia, gait steady   Clinical Impression/Field Tx: Vasovagal syncope.  EMS called immediately to respond to the site for further evaluation.  Patient placed into a reclined position.  Patient not displaying active signs or symptoms of anaphylaxis.  Upon regaining consciousness, patient was alert and oriented x4.  Once the patient demonstrated ability to control airway, he was given candy and water.  EMS arrived and an EKG and BGL were performed, both of which were normal.  Vital signs were stable.   Instructed patient to consult their PCP regarding the post-vaccination reaction.  Patient instructed to go to emergency department should they develop chest pain, difficulty breathing, swelling of the face/lips/mouth/tongue/throat, or cramping abdominal pain with nausea/vomiting, as these are signs of possible anaphylaxis that requires immediate intervention.     Medications administered: None   Disposition:  FD EMS called to the scene for further evaluation.  Patient elected to go home after evaluation by EMS.
PRIOR_VAX: Syncope following vaccines at pediatrician's office

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was coherent during initial injection, as I removed my gloves and asked he remain in the waiting area for 15 minutes his chin fell to his chest and he began to breath heavily. I spoke to him and there was no response. He then began making snoring type noises and lifted his head but again was unresponsive. Patient then slumped sideways in the chair. I made one last attempt to arouse him with firm strikes to the chest and calling his name. I retrieved the EpiPen from the e-kit and as I removed it from the box he became conscious. He opened his eyes and gasped and tremored slightly. He was not immediately responsive verbally. I observed him carefully to evaluate if he was going to have a seizure, but he then became coherent. He was alert and oriented to time and place but did ask how ling it had been since the vaccine. He admitted to having a problem with needles and stated that was the root of the reaction. He does not remember any reactions to previous vaccines but also could not recall his last vaccination. We brought the patient water and offered snacks while he recovered in the patient care area. Approximately 20-30 minutes after the initial event the patient began vomiting. After a few minutes of vomiting he said he felt a little better and wanted to go to his car to lay down. Multiple times we asked if we could call someone to come pick him up and offered to have him seen by paramedics that happened to be shopping in store. He declined both offers and stated he would lie down in his car and call someone if he did not feel well after awhile. Staff checked on him in his car and he was instructed to call in before leaving. Upon trying to check on him again it was noted his car was gone. I called the patient and he assured me he was ok and he was now at home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Got covid vax (Moderna) during recovery from MASSIVE surgery for stage 4 endometriosis. HUGE amounts taken off my entire pelvic bowl and sidewalls, in adding to tons between my rectum and vagina, in addition to having to remove my Left ovary, uterus, both fallopian tubes, and appendix. Though I was towards the end of my 1st stage of recovery (took TONS of different types of meds from Jan 28 when surgery happened, though the first week of March...I HATE meds and normally take 0, but due to surgery I had to take many hundreds of pills, of various kinds, to mitigate pain, mitigate the side effects of the pain meds, NSAIDS, and muscle relaxers. Marijuana is a safer, non-addictive, low-no side-effect med I chose to start taking ASAP so I could get off everything that was prescribed because prescriptions scrambled my brain and made me feel terrible.   At the time of 1st vax on Feb 25, no shocking or adverse reactions occurred, but I was still on muscle relaxers (flexerol) taking 7.5mg multiple times a day in addition to the medicinal marijuana pills and some advil I was still taking.   At the time of vax 2 on March 25, I was not taking anything. Not even medicinal marijuana. The night after I started taking this was when I believe the muscle spasms came back in significant length and at significant level of pain #6. They continued and i reported to my PCP and my GYN who did surgery. I wasn't worried about the spasms...I knew how to control them and they were nothing compared to the extraordinary pain of all of Feb, but they were significant as a side effect of my vax #2  After a week or so the symptoms had gradually diminished.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within seconds of receiving the vaccine, I had a strong metallic taste in my mouth. My husband and I sat in our car for the 15 minutes required and I thought I was feeling a bit off, but also was trying to figure out if anyone else had experienced the metallic taste. After our 15 minutes wait period, we left to head back home. On the way home, about 30-40 minutes after I received the vaccine, I started to feel really warm. Then my neck started to feel really hot and when I swallowed it felt like I had a knot in my throat. As far as I know, I'm not allergic to anything, but realized there was something seriously wrong with my body and had my husband get off the freeway so I could get some water and possibly go to an urgent care. It also doesn't help that my heart was racing and I started panicking because it felt like my throat was starting to close up. When the initial anxiety of what was happening calmed down, we carefully drove home and I called the urgent care nurse line at my doctor's office. The nurse on the line told me to take a Benadryl and to take another one 6 hours later. He said that I was having an adverse reaction and if things got worse go into the ER . Luckily things calmed down after a while but the metallic taste stayed for two days. I've been advised to not get the 2nd dose, which I'm honestly not comfortable getting at this point either.
LAB_DATA: Nurse should have the records of the conversation.

I have pulled muscles, tendons and ligaments from the chest compressions which were questionable but since that day have experienced tingling in upper body and arms and have felt bad. SYMPTOM_TEXT: We are a Pharmacy. Today, April 9, 2021, we had a patient. She was scheduled for her first dose of the Pfizer vaccine at 9:30 am. The pharmacy manager gave her the vaccine inside the store at around 9:30 am. She was accompanied by her husband. After the shot, she sat down in one of the chairs in front of the pharmacy to wait for the mandatory 15 minutes wait for any reactions. At 9:43 am, we noticed that she was looking a bit dizzy. As we were approaching her, she slid down the chair and became unconscious. Luckily her husband was right beside her and caught her before she fell. Pharmacy manager then helped her husband to quickly lay her down flat on her back. The husband asked to call 911. The pharmacy technician was there to assist and she called 911. The patient regained consciousness roughly around 30 seconds after she fainted. She was alert and breathing normally. We asked again if they wanted us to continue calling 911. They said yes. Roughly 5 mins later, the paramedics came and assisted the patient. The sugar was good, blood pressure was good, temperature was good. They asked her if she wanted to go to the hospital. The patient denied. The paramedics left and the patient stayed for more time at the pharmacy and eventually left.

Per ED report, patient went to Pharmacy to get her 2nd COVID 19 vaccine on 3/29/2021 ~ 1 pm. She first felt fine, but ~ 2 pm she started having breakout of her rash, a dry cough and slightly raspy throat as well as facial swelling. She came to the Outpatient Center where she usually receives Xolair for her idiopathic anaphylaxis q 2 weeks, where she received a total of 300 mg of IV diphenhydramine and 40 mg of IV famotidine, after which they sent her to the ED for further observation and medication administration. Pt with known hx of seizures, rec'd her 2nd dose Pfizer at COVID-19 vaccine clinic @1505.  Pt had "aura" while in observation area w/ husband and observation RN.  Pt took her own home Ativan dose PO.  At approx 1519, pt had focal seizure with mild arm flexion; no head/oral trauma; no falls/injury.  Her husband reported this to be a normal seizure for her and stated her seizures usually last <5min.  At 1521, pt was taken to extended observation area room via personal wheelchair; VS were stable upon arrival to extended observation.  The Dr.was also notified and came to observation room for evaluation @1525.  Per husband, seizure lasted approx 10 mins.  Pt then post-ictal and responsive.  VS obtained & stable; BP129/84, HR99, RR20, O2 Sat97% on RA.  Approx 1543, pt had second seizure while sitting in wheelchair.  MD  & 2RNs at bedside for safety.  911 was called at this time.  IV access established 22g R wrist with IVF NS infusing.  Placed pt on 2L O2 via NC per MD request.  VS remained stable throughout seizure.  Patient post-ictal, verbal, interacting, maintaining own airway.  Paramedics arrived @ 1603; report given to medics and transferred to the Hospital for further valuation by ambulance.
OTHER_MEDS: Full medication history unknown, however, patient took her home Ativan shortly after receiving the vaccine because she felt an aura like she was about to have a seizure.
ALLERGIES: levothyroxine, metoclopramide, pregabalin, venlafaxine, gluten meal, lactulose

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 23 yo FM who received first dose of Pfizer vaccine and then was noted to have shortness of breath and complaining tongue closing sensation immediately after at Vaccine Clinic --I was called to evaluate the patient. When I arrived patient was laying down on a chair with a friend, shaking with seizure like activity but alert and oriented to person place and time. Upon my arrival she was shaking, vomited x 1 and then complained about chest pain.   Vitals upon my arrival: HR 58, o2 100% RR appeared to be around 22-24 (hyperventilating) BP 88 systolic (manual)--repeated by medics upon arrival minutes later 110/72.   Given throat closing sensation, vomiting, shortness of breath I advised to call 911 and ordered Epinephrine x 1 which was given by RN immediately. Pt was then placed on the grown chin up, she continued to shake throughout entire body but continued to be alert and oriented. Medics then arrived on seen, started an IV, glucose by medics 84, IVF started by medics. Pt was transported to ER via medics.   Pt is not a patient, last visit 2017. Pt did state she has hx of POTS and DRESS syndrome to Lamictal. Reports taking cetirizine this AM, Zofran and Oxycodone and Baclofen (prescribed by external PCP?).   Prior to transport to ER pt continued to be alert oriented, but shaking and twitching throughout her body. MD verbally communicated to patient to not receive the 2nd dose given her severe anaphylaxis like reaction to the first dose of the vaccine. Pt can be referred to allergist after ER follow up by PCP.  Denied pregnancy.
CUR_ILL: Gender dysphoria, Postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Subacute thyroiditis This generally healthy patient, with no history of thyroid disease, developed subacute thyroiditis (SAT) following an influenza vaccination.  He experienced no viral infection symptoms in the weeks preceding the vaccination, nor during the weeks after the vaccination when the SAT symptoms developed.  He spent approximately 3 months in phase 1 (thyrotoxic), followed by a 1 month transition to hypo-thyroid, followed by a 1 year gradual transition to normal thyroid function.  The patient sought medical care for his thyrotoxic symptoms several times before they were correctly diagnosed almost 3 months post vaccination. In the several days following the vaccination, mild soreness at the upper left arm injection site spread up over the shoulder and into the left side of the neck, where it gradually worsened over the next 2 weeks.  12 days post vaccination, the patient visited his Primary Care Physician (PCP) for this pain, which was most prominent in the left neck, but also present on the left side of the head and the anterior and posterior neck.  The patient also noted some throat discomfort with swallowing.  Examination revealed possible thyroid swelling, but no indications of respiratory infection.  Over the next 2.5 months, his neck pain persisted, with increasing anterior neck pain, sometimes radiating to the jaw and ears.  Discomfort with swallowing increased, and headaches were no longer confined to the left side of the head.  The patient also felt progressively unwell, with difficulty sleeping, body aches, and increasingly frequent chills.  (Though he did not measure his temperature.)  87 days post vaccination, the patient again sought care from his PCP.  He had started measuring his temperature in recent days and found it varying from 96 to 102 degrees F.  At this point, his thyroid was more clearly painful when palpated, so additional lab tests were ordered on 2020 March 2.  High sed rate (93 mm/hr), high Free T4 (2.10 ng/dL), and very low Thyroid Stimulating Hormone (TSH, < 0.005 uIU/mL) indicated subacute thyroiditis (SAT) in the thyrotoxic phase, and the patient was referred to endocrinologist.  Additional tests over the next 3 weeks confirmed the SAT diagnosis.  These included Thyroid Stimulating Immunoglobulin (< 1.0), Free T3 (7.40 pg/mL), a thyroid ultrasound (enlarged with increased vascularity), and thyroid radioactive iodine uptake (0.9% at 6 hours, and 0.8% at 24 hours).  At 124 days post-vaccination (2020 April 8), the patient's thyrotoxic symptoms had largely resolved, consistent with the hypo-thyroid c ondition indicated by lab tests:  TSH = 19.600 uIU/mL, Free T4 = 0.67 ng/dL, and Free T3 = 2.50 pg/mL.  Periodic TSH and Free T4 tests over the next year showed gradual recovery to normal thyroid function on 2021/03/22 (TSH = 3.75 uIU/mL, Free T4 = 0.91 ng/dL).

I had my three small children with me and wanted to get them home. I called my husband who is a physician and told him everything I was experiencing. He told me to stay in the store to see how things went. I then drove home to monitor my symptoms. I had post nasal drip and it exacerbated over the next few weeks. I was on two different antibiotics because it felt like I had a bad ear infection. It never went away. I saw an ENT and my tympanaplasty that I had as a child blew. I have a large hole in my ear drum currently and very dizzy. I am getting a CT of my ear this Wednesday and I will have to have surgery in the next few months for another tympanoplasty.

Got shot in right arm. Sat in waiting area and within 5 - 7 min felt sick and faint. Dropped to the floor and I could not move. I heard people wanting to sit me up to get me in a chair but I could not move on my own. They lifted me and then I went out completely. I remember dreaming and then within seconds, that is what I was told, I could hear them. I then was taken to an area that they  checked my pulse, BP, and sugar. Blood pressure, I believe was around 92. I usually run around 120 but can run lower. They called an ambulance because I was unresponsive for a bit while on the floor. I was given IV fluids because of concern with BP. I was aware the rest of the time. I felt nauseous, shaky, cold, thirsty, and very weak. I went to the hospital and they did a CBC and differential as well as a chest xray. All were very good. They also did an EKG which was ok. I started to feel better and the doctor said I could drink and since I felt hungry and had a small protein bar. I was discharged around 12:15p. I continued to feel very weak, some nausea, some diarrhea and a slight headache. I woke in the morning very dizzy and off balance with a sore arm, a little nausea and weak. On 4/8/21 I woke up feeling very weak in my limbs. Headache, sore arm and nausea were gone.  By the end of the day the weakness was a bit improved. By 4/9/21 the weakness in my limbs was much better.  Still get a little dizzy if I bend over.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was scheduled for an appointment for a Johnson &Johnson  covid-19 vaccine through a drive thru Thursday April 8, 2021 @12:45pm. We arrived early and he received the vaccine at 12:15pm, waited 30 minutes for reaction and he was feeling fine. Later that same evening, the patient was driving to work on the freeway when he felt a dry throat so he coughed hard, at that cough he felt a massive pain in his head, like his "head was going to explode." He immediately had tunnel vision closing in on him, so he pulled over and later woke up in our parked car with flashing emergency lights on, parked on the shoulder of the freeway. Disoriented and confused why he was there, he looked at his watch and saw he lost 15 minutes when he had passed out. MY HUSBAND COULD HAVE BEEN SERIOUSLY INJURED OR KILLED IF HE HAD NOT PULLED HIMSELF OVER WHEN PASSING OUT. Today we reported this to our doctors office and to you!

Patient received first dose of Pfizer covid-19 vaccine on 4/9/2021 at 1800 with her mother in attendance  after consent was acquired.  At 1805 patient began to feel hot and nauseous. The patient thought she was going to vomit, so she left her chair in the waiting area to head to the restroom at the back of the store.  at 1807,  Upon rising the patient became weak in the knees and began to collapse.  The patient's mother initially supported the patient and I was called to assist the patient to the floor. The patient was very pale in appearance as she was assisted gently to the floor, avoiding any injury.  EMS was called shortly after the event around 1810. The patient remained conscious however was a bit disoriented initially while lying on the floor.  The patient recovered quickly, however remained nauseous and complained of feeling hot. Upon questioning the patient, she had not eaten since lunch at school at 1300. The patient was given a cold water and a sprite, of which she had a couple of drinks out of each. The patient was relocated back into a chair at 1815 as she was feeling much better. EMS arrived at 1821. EMS performed a general assessment and a blood pressure check resulting in 130/80. The patient's mother dismissed any further treatment from EMS.  EMS exited the building at 1827.  The patient and mother waited in the store for a while longer.  Both patient and mother exited on their own, denying escort from associates at 1840.
PRIOR_VAX: gardasil- fainted

PT c/o dizziness/lightheaded at 12:44 & taken to room to lie down.  Note by  MD:  Notified by Nurse  that the patient had just received COVID 19 vaccine and is feeling dizzy and not feeling well.  Patient was already brought to exam room 1 for further monitoring and assessment.  In the exam room, patient is sitting up talking to MA .   reports that patient's O2 Saturation is 98%.   While I was talking to the patient, patient states the lips and face are having symptoms of tingling and with sensation of swelling. Patient also states feeling dizzy, sleepy, nausea, and lethargic.  I asked patient to lay down on exam table instead of sitting up.  I immediately place patient's legs up with the help of patient's friend.  On exam, patient is becoming more pale. No diaphoresis. Patient has sign of becoming less arousable. Patient states vision becoming more blurred and patient was near passing out.  Due to above progressing and escalating symptoms, possible anaphylactic reaction to COVID 19 vaccine is considered. I immediately call for assistance from nursing staff to bring EpiPen.  Dr.arrived with EpiPen in the exam room.  Patient continues to have progressing symptom of difficulty with arousal in a near syncopal state.  Patient is becoming less alert.  Decision is to give EpiPen injection to reverse potential progressive and impending anaphylactic reaction with sign of progressive hypotension.  Blood pressure was not able to be taken before the EpiPen was given due to patient's rapid progressing symptoms.   EpiPen injection to right thigh done by Dr..  After the injection of EpiPen patient had nausea with dry heave.  No vomiting.   BP taken in right arm in supine position.  BP is 110/70.  Pulse Oximeter: Pulse 93.  O2 Saturation 96%.   Heart exam: RRR no murmur.  Lungs: no rales. no wheeze. breath sound equal and bilateral.   Few minutes after the injection of EpiPen, patient states is having improvement of blurred vision and blurred vision has gradually resolved.  Patient is also more arousable and alert.  Patient still has nausea.   Patient reports feeling improvement.   Paramedic arrived and evaluated the patient.  Patient transported to ER by paramedic around 1:22 pm.  At time of transport, patient is in stable condition.  Patient is awake, alert and answer all questions appropriately.   Per patient's friend, patient had symptom of tingling sensation of the lips and face and also urticaria 3 hours after receiving 1st dose of Moderna COVID 19 vaccine  which was 1 month ago.  Patient's friend learned about this 1 day after the patient had the vaccine.  Unclear if patient received any treatment for such.  Patient states never had other vaccine reaction in the past.
PRIOR_VAX: Pt reported tingling lips that self-resolved

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Conjunctivitis formed in my left eye suddenly (same side of the body where I got the shot). I only noticed when I got out of the shower and looked in the mirror. After that I noticed my eye was tearing and goopy. It was very red for an hour or two and then it started to improve. The redness went down considerably by 10:30pm, but my eye remained slightly goopy and irritated for 2 days. I was able to continue wearing the same pair of contacts. It just went away on its own.  I wore my contacts as a test to see if it were truly a bacterial or viral conjunctivitis I contracted by coincidence, but I knew it was not. I don't go anywhere. The fact that it went away on its own so quickly was confirmation that it was a side effect.   It is worth saying that I have also experienced pink eye from a virus in the past. Maybe my body is more susceptible.

We gave patient the vaccine and advised him to wait for the CDC recommended 15 minutes observation time. He decided to leave after just a few minutes, despite his dad (who was with him) questioning the decision and suggesting he stay 15 minutes. I was then told by a member of management through our walkie-talkie system that they needed me at the front register immediately because someone passed out after getting a vaccine. I was there within the minute with my vaccine emergency bag. Upon arriving, the patient was already awake, talking, and sitting in a chair. He also was profusely sweating. He stated he's never experienced anything like this before. He said he normally has low blood pressure. He starting drinking some water. When I checked his blood pressure it was so low the machine gave an error message. Throughout this time, the patient progressively was feeling better and eventually wound up laughing and smiling. Him and his father said that he would be ok and that he was feeling himself. I told him to sit for a bit more before leaving and stay as long as he wants. I called him later that evening to check on him and had to leave a voicemail. His father called back 2 days later and said he's been fine.

He stated he was experiencing nausea while sitting in the chair, and said he started to feel like he was going to faint again. Immediate pain at injection site as expected , as well as fever, headache, chills, fatigue. Towards evening these symptoms worsened. (not adverse).  I hardly slept. (all these not worrisome to me) I'm so glad my vaccine provider warned me that with underlying conditions, the vaccine could make them flare up. Which they did. In the morning I had widespread pain all over. Severe headache, and shortness of breath. Because I already have near emphysema hypoxemia oxygen levels, I checked my Oximeter and my blood oxygen was in the dangerously low 70's.  It stayed there until I put my oxygen concentrator on. Monitoring oxygen levels all day, I was able to keep it in the 80's to 90's, which helped.  40 hrs after injection , symptoms already fading away. All my adverse events were related to underlying conditions responding to the inflammation of the immune response. I feel  protected, glad I had the oxygen handy,  and I feel great about the  J & J vaccine!

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 6 hours after receiving the vaccine I started getting a headache and felt chills. I was on my way to a hotel before leaving for a flight the next morning and was driving. When I stopped driving and attempted to exit my car, I experienced dizziness and stroke like symptoms. My legs would not hold me up and I felt as if I would pass out in the road. I held on to the car for several minutes until the feeling abated somewhat. Then I made my way unsteadily into the  hotel building and had to sit down for several minutes. My heart was beating rapidly and I felt strange so I took one of my nitroglycerin and also took an extra 12.5 mg Coreg.  After being taken to my room, I laid on the bed and continued to feel  weak, lightheaded and became very nauseous. I got out my pulse oximeter and my pulse was 95.  I took another Coreg and it seemed to slow it down for a little while but again it started racing and I continued to be nauseous and broke out in sweats and my pulse got back up to 100. I took another nitroglycerin and a baby aspirin in case I was having a heart attack. Then I took another Coreg. My pulse rate finally slowed down. I slept intermittently until going to the airport at 5 a.m.  I still felt weak and nauseous and very tired.
OTHER_MEDS: Coreg, Digoxin, Spironolactone, Metformin, Irbesartan, levothyroxine, baby aspirin

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my vaccine about 3pm Sat. April 3rd. About an hour or so later I started to feel ?run down? but nothing major. At 9pm I began getting chills but did not feel feverish. By 9:15 my body was aggressively trembling. Even my teeth were chattering. I could not control the shaking. I put many layers of blankets on me and turned my heat up to 80 in an effort to get warm. At some point I dozed off. I woke up at 12:30am and had a fever of a little over 101 degrees.  I fell asleep about 3am, still aggressively shaking.  I woke up at 9am (April 4th) and my head was throbbing. My fever was now 102.2. Also, every muscle in my back and shoulders ached. I sat up because I needed to get to the kitchen for some water. Once I stood up, my body felt like it was weighed down by heavy sandbags. I could barely walk to my kitchen and back. I went back to bed and covered up in massive blankets and tried to stay still. I did not take any pain reliever because I was too nervous to.  I never had any nausea but smells bothered me and I had no appetite. My fever stayed at 102.2 until I went to sleep (around 10pm).  Monday (April 5th) I still had chills but much milder. My temp was just over 101 all day. My head felt better but my muscles still hurt. By late evening (10pm) my fever was just over 99 degrees. I was feeling better and I no longer had chills.  Tuesday (April 6th) I woke up fever free. I felt mostly normal again except for my muscle aches.  Today is Friday (April 9th) and I continue to have muscle aches. The worst of it is in my lower back and it?s pretty severe. It feels like I lifted heavy weights with my lower back muscles. I have not been seen by a Doctor yet as I have no insurance. I?m not sure if I need to or not.   I wanted to contact you because I am a healthy person and what I experienced was BRUTAL. I have NO IDEA how a frail or vulnerable person could go through what I went through. Also, people need to know that they may have to take time off of work to deal with these side effects.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: cardiac arrest Narrative:  Patient received dose 2 series of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine. First dose was received on 1/17/21 and second dose received 2/14/21. After both doses patient was observed for 15 minutes and did not have any adverse reaction per administering RN. No data in database or database as to any other adverse events occurring 15 minutes post-vaccination. On 3/20/21, EMS was called to patient's home who was discovered on the floor with an unknown breathing status and pulse. AED was attached to the patient. A very weak pulse was found and patient had agonal respirations. Cardiac monitor was attached to patient with a HR of 32. 1mg of atropine was administered and patient's rhythm changed to PEA with no respirations or pulse. Per patient's wife and son, he was a DNR, therefore all resuscitation attempts were stopped (patient was never admitted to the hospital). Patient was never known to be previously positive to COVID. PMH that may have predisposed patient to this adverse event leading to death include h/o DVT on chronic anticoagulation, COPD, and abdominal aortic aneurysm. There is insufficient information to determine the exact cause of death or what led to the cardiac arrest given that the time from last vaccination to the adverse event was almost a month apart.
Death Narrative: already reported VAER for hospitalization on 3/3; the patient subsequently died once transferred to SNF

Narrative: Patient admitted 2/19/2021 after receiving the 1st COVID-19 vaccine (Moderna; Lot# 031M20A; Exp 08/05/2021). Patient experienced minor reaction with inflammation/pain of the RUE and swelling. COVID-19 on 2/19/2021 negative, as well as CXR unremarkable. tongue paresthesia Narrative:  Immediately following administration of first dose of Pfizer COVID19 vaccine, patient reported pruritus, bumps on sides of R then L neck, and tingling/stinging sensation of the R side of her tongue without swelling of tongue/lips elsewhere. Patient took personal supply of diphenhydramine 50mg and was transported to ED for further evaluation. Upon arrival to ED, no additional symptoms reported. She denied any areas of urticaria/hives at that time and stated the neck is the only area of rash she noted, and she currently has pruritus only around the neck area and still notes small bumps. Her tongue felt improved but not normal and she denied any tongue/oral swelling, wheezing, dyspnea, chest pain, syncope, LH, palpitations, confusion, n/v/d/abd pain HA, focal neurological complaints, seizures, or any other acute symptoms. Patient had an extensive history of multiple other allergies. Diagnosis included early angioedema and second dose not recommended by ED provider. Methylprednisolone and famotidine administered in ED. Patient discharged from ED with prednisone and famotidine. Previously prescribed epinephrine for anaphylactic seafood allergy.

paresthesia in hands, shortness of breath  Narrative:  First dose of Pfizer COVID19 vaccine administered 2/13/21. No  adverse effects documented. Second dose received 3/5/21. On 3/9/21, patient presented to ED with SOB, cough, and wheezing. Symptoms and finding consistent with COPD exacerbation with bilateral bacterial PNA. Also found to have new  onset atrial fibrillation with tachycardia. Unclear if any respiratory symptoms were related to vaccine. Patient was admitted and transferred to hospital with diagnosis of COPD exacerbation and AFib with RVR. Per provider notes, no indication that an allergy was suspected. Patient was treated methylprednisolone, ceftriaxone, and azithromycin for PNA as well as diltiazem and apixaban for new onset AFib. Was discharge 3/11/21. Patient presented 4/1/21 at cardiology  follow-up appointment and reported he developed paresthesias  after second Pfizer dose. Right hand worse than left. Stated he now has difficulty holding a pen. No documentation of this during admission. Unclear if related to vaccine, no treatment documented. Further work up pending at time of reported.
